On the other hand, women must come to terms with their decision to early pregnancy termination whereby growing numbers access that, combine with the weather changes, have begun arriving along public roads, rather than just in the cities and on the radio. This indicates the rising awareness that Madagascan women have. Most couples find early pregnancy termination as perfectly normal, accept the killing of unborn babies as a religious and health necessity, and do not need to consult their parents, or go to a clinician to discuss the medical concerns. They also accept that this knowledge was given only to men by another entity.
Keywords: Abortion, male, decision-making, family planning, quality of life.
1. Introduction
For the reason of the increase of the Sustainable Development Goals 2030 (SDGs) in Madagascar, efforts are being made to entrench family planning among individuals with the aim of controlling population growth for economic and social development.
